Anaheim Police Department

************************************************************************


A message was sent to you regarding record request #26-1755:

Dear Requestor,

&nbsp;

The Anaheim Police Department received your request dated February 23, 2026, wherein you have requested the following:



...

&nbsp;

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All calls for service to Disneyland Resort, California Adventure Park, and/or Downtown Disney District between the dates of January 2025 through when this request is processed.

2) All, if any, arrest records involving individuals that were in either Disneyland Resort, California Adventure Park, or Downtown Disney District at time of arrest between the dates of January 2025 to when this request is processed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.



...



The Anaheim Police Department has has identified records for production and these have been published to our NextRequest portal.



Additionally, your request seeks information that is not contemporaneous. Per&nbsp;Kinney v Superior Court of Kern County, et al. 77 Cal.App.5th 168, 292 Cal.Rptr.3d 392, the APD may limit the disclosure of arrest information to that which is contemporaneous. Accordingly, you may find APD's arrest log online at the following link:&nbsp;https://local.anaheim.net/images/articles/4119/Arrest_Log.xml

&nbsp;

Other record(s) you seek may be withheld from production if they fall within any of the following exemptions to the Public Records Act:

&nbsp;

·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Police investigatory records are generally exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §7923.600(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Documents reflecting police techniques or "security procedures" are expressly exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §7923.600(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Personal contact information is exempt from disclosure. [Government Code §7922.000];



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You are not the victim of the subject incident, nor have you provided evidence that you are an authorized representative thereof, and the report is exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §7923.615(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Victims of certain types of crimes including sexual assault may request that their identity be withheld per Government Code §7923.615(a);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Juvenile information is confidential (Welfare and Institutions Code §§ 827 and 828);



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The records may be related to ongoing investigations and therefore are exempt from disclosure pursuant to Government Code §§7927.500, 7929.000, and 7923.600(a) (See also, Haynie v. Superior Court (2001) 26 Cal.4th 1061; Williams v. Superior Court (1993) 5 Cal.4th 337; Rivero v. Superior Court (1997) 54 Cal.App.4th 1048; Rackauckas v. Superior Court (2002) 104 Cal.App.4th 169; Commission on Peace Officer Standards and Training v. Superior Court (2007) 42 Cal.4th 278; New York Times v. Superior Court (1997) 52 Cal.App.4th 97; and 91 Ops. Cal.Atty.Gen. 11 (2008));&nbsp;



·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The subject investigation relates to potential criminal prosecution.&nbsp;Evidence gathered as part of a criminal investigation is by its nature confidential.&nbsp;Investigative files are therefore privileged so long as the need for confidentiality outweighs the benefits of disclosure in the particular case.&nbsp;County of Orange v Superior Court (Wu) (2000) 79 CA4th 759, 765, 768, 94 CR2d 261, 264, 266; Evidence Code section 1040(b).

&nbsp;



Without waiving, and subject to, the foregoing exemptions, APD has identified records for production and these have been published to our NextRequest portal.





&nbsp;

Sincerely,



ANAHEIM POLICE DEPARTMENT

RECORDS SECTION








************************************************************************                          
